question over the years

00:01:46.460 --> 00:01:49.340
and asked how we failed and
asked how failures like this

00:01:49.340 --> 00:01:50.390
occur.

00:01:50.390 --> 00:01:52.660
One evening he and I
had a conversation,

00:01:52.660 --> 00:01:54.880
likely over a bottle
of scotch, and we

00:01:54.880 --> 00:01:57.790
started realizing that
disaster after disaster,

00:01:57.790 --> 00:01:59.010
there'd be a commission.

00:01:59.010 --> 00:02:00.279
There'd be articles.

00:02:00.279 --> 00:02:02.070
There'd be journalists
who would pursue it.

00:02:02.070 --> 00:02:03.640
And someone would
come out, who'd

00:02:03.640 --> 00:02:07.150
stand out, who had predicted
that disaster in great detail

00:02:07.150 --> 00:02:08.370
and been ignored.

00:02:08.370 --> 00:02:11.780
We realized there seemed to
be a pattern of these people,

00:02:11.780 --> 00:02:14.250
and that, perhaps, was
worth looking into further.

00:02:14.250 --> 00:02:16.830
In Greek mythology, there
was a woman named Cassandra.

00:02:16.830 --> 00:02:18.730
She was a beautiful
mortal, and she

00:02:18.730 --> 00:02:20.360
refused to sleep with Apollo.

00:02:20.360 --> 00:02:23.260
Apollo's curse to her
was that every time she

00:02:23.260 --> 00:02:25.010
foretold disaster--
in fact, he allowed

00:02:25.010 --> 00:02:28.390
her to foretell disasters--
she would be ignored.

00:02:28.390 --> 00:02:31.610
Cassandra then, being from
Troy, saw the sack of her city,

00:02:31.610 --> 00:02:34.235
saw her brothers killed,
saw her family destroyed,

00:02:34.235 --> 00:02:36.610
her home destroyed, her entire
city burned to the ground.

00:02:36.610 --> 00:02:38.440
She saw this in
perfect detail, well

00:02:38.440 --> 00:02:40.820
before it occurred, and
warned and warned and warned.

00:02:40.820 --> 00:02:43.360
And Cassandra went
crazy with her warnings,

00:02:43.360 --> 00:02:45.250
crazy that no one
listened to her.

00:02:45.250 --> 00:02:49.140
So we decided to go look
for modern-day Cassandras.

00:02:49.140 --> 00:02:51.510
And boy, did we find them.

00:02:51.510 --> 00:02:55.100
What we found was a huge number
of people who were ignored--

00:02:55.100 --> 00:02:57.720
but not just warnings,
not sandwich plate,

00:02:57.720 --> 00:02:59.610
crazy people on the
street corner saying

00:02:59.610 --> 00:03:02.990
the sky is going to fall, but
people with shockingly clear,

00:03:02.990 --> 00:03:06.620
data-driven warnings,
eminently qualified experts

00:03:06.620 --> 00:03:10.150
who were telling us about
events of massive consequence.

00:03:10.150 --> 00:03:12.120
You know, yes, we
are right to ignore

00:03:12.120 --> 00:03:13.680
many warnings of
disaster, but there

00:03:13.680 --> 00:03:15.506
are some we have to listen to.

00:03:15.506 --> 00:03:17.130
And when we don't
find these Cassandras

00:03:17.130 --> 00:03:20.990
and we don't listen
to them, people die.

00:03:20.990 --> 00:03:22.760
I'll talk about a
couple examples of this.

00:03:22.760 --> 00:03:25.510
Some of these are
awfully painful.

00:03:25.510 --> 00:03:27.910
We went out and interviewed
as many of the Cassandras

00:03:27.910 --> 00:03:29.140
as we could find.

00:03:29.140 --> 00:03:31.840
And it was a fascinating
and sad experience.

00:03:31.840 --> 00:03:32.620
We learned a lot.

00:03:32.620 --> 00:03:34.869
These are extraordinary
people who gave these warnings

00:03:34.869 --> 00:03:36.010
and were ignored.

00:03:36.010 --> 00:03:38.380
Another example of a
Cassandra that was ignored,

00:03:38.380 --> 00:03:41.500
another extremely poignant
example, is Charlie Allen.

00:03:41.500 --> 00:03:43.480
Charlie was the National
Intelligence Officer

00:03:43.480 --> 00:03:44.200
for Warning.

00:03:44.200 --> 00:03:46.660
This is a job in an
organization called

00:03:46.660 --> 00:03:48.250
the National
Intelligence Council that

00:03:48.250 --> 00:03:49.780
sits above the CIA.

00:03:49.780 --> 00:03:52.330
Charlie was a career
intelligence professional,

00:03:52.330 --> 00:03:55.420
and he realized in '89
that Saddam Hussein

00:03:55.420 --> 00:03:57.770
was going to invade Kuwait.

00:03:57.770 --> 00:03:59.810
Charlie had a variety
of intelligence

00:03:59.810 --> 00:04:02.319
that was giving him high
confidence of this concern,

00:04:02.319 --> 00:04:03.860
and he brought it
to the interagency.

00:04:03.860 --> 00:04:05.890
He brought it to the DoD,
brought it to the State,

00:04:05.890 --> 00:04:08.140
brought it to the deputies,
brought it to the cabinet.

00:04:08.140 --> 00:04:12.120
Everybody ignored Charlie
all the way along the line.

00:04:12.120 --> 00:04:13.620
He had a power to
write something

00:04:13.620 --> 00:04:15.390
called a warning of war.

00:04:15.390 --> 00:04:17.070
By virtue of his
position, he could

00:04:17.070 --> 00:04:19.500
write a letter that would
land on the president's desk.

00:04:19.500 --> 00:04:21.419
So Charlie wrote
the warning of war.

00:04:21.419 --> 00:04:22.710
It ended up at the White House.

00:04:22.710 --> 00:04:25.126
The president looked at it,
and it said, I am telling you,

00:04:25.126 --> 00:04:27.060
Saddam Hussein
will invade Kuwait.

00:04:27.060 --> 00:04:29.940
It might be a few months from
now, but it's coming soon.

00:04:29.940 --> 00:04:31.930
Charlie had extraordinary
confidence in this.

00:04:31.930 --> 00:04:33.180
And again, it was data-driven.

00:04:33.180 --> 00:04:36.701
Of course, Charlie was
ignored, and the First Gulf War

00:04:36.701 --> 00:04:37.200
occurred.

00:04:37.200 --> 00:04:38.750
We call it the First
Gulf War because then we

00:04:38.750 --> 00:04:39.990
had a Second Gulf War.

00:04:39.990 --> 00:04:42.840
If you think about what
ended up occurring, the price

00:04:42.840 --> 00:04:45.690
we paid from the First Gulf
War, from Saddam's invasion

00:04:45.690 --> 00:04:47.640
of Kuwait, it's
fairly extraordinary.

00:04:47.640 --> 00:04:49.890
One thing that might
not be as obvious

00:04:49.890 --> 00:04:52.750
is that American troop
presence in Saudi Arabia--

00:04:52.750 --> 00:04:55.440
we put troops there to protect
Saudi Arabia at this moment--

00:04:55.440 --> 00:04:58.120
was the entire raison
d'etre of al-Qaeda.

00:04:58.120 --> 00:05:00.600
Al-Qaeda did not exist
until we put troops there.

00:05:00.600 --> 00:05:02.655
Al-Qaeda had no
reason, no raison

00:05:02.655 --> 00:05:03.900
d'etre until we did that.

00:05:03.900 --> 00:05:06.510
Al-Qaeda was born because
we put troops there,

00:05:06.510 --> 00:05:07.787
because Saddam invaded Kuwait.

00:05:07.787 --> 00:05:09.370
Of course, Saddam's
invasion of Kuwait

00:05:09.370 --> 00:05:11.400
and the First Gulf
War and al-Qaeda

00:05:11.400 --> 00:05:13.230
led to the Second Gulf War.

00:05:13.230 --> 00:05:17.400
We're talking about 25 years of
destabilization in the region,

00:05:17.400 --> 00:05:21.630
trillions of dollars of treasure
spent, millions of lives lost.

00:05:21.630 --> 00:05:23.342
And Charlie, the man
who got it right,

00:05:23.342 --> 00:05:25.050
well, he was threatened
with being fired.

00:05:25.050 --> 00:05:27.740
He was screamed at, yelled
at for giving the warning.

00:05:27.740 --> 00:05:30.300
And the National Intelligence
Officer for Warning position

00:05:30.300 --> 00:05:32.160
has since been abolished.

00:05:32.160 --> 00:05:34.830
We're not very good at
listening to these people.

00:05:34.830 --> 00:05:38.720
The final example I'll
give is of Fukushima.

00:05:38.720 --> 00:05:43.000
Dr. Okamura is a noted
seismologist in Japan.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:46.020
And when the Fukushima Daiichi
Nuclear Plant was being built,

00:05:46.020 --> 00:05:48.120
he came to them in every
open hearing and said,

00:05:48.120 --> 00:05:50.490
you cannot build this nuclear
reactor where you are.

00:05:50.490 --> 00:05:52.380
You are too close
to the shoreline.

00:05:52.380 --> 00:05:53.620
You are too low.

00:05:53.620 --> 00:05:56.310
If you do, a tsunami will
come and will destroy it.

00:05:56.310 --> 00:05:57.300
He knew the tsunami.

00:05:57.300 --> 00:05:58.092
He knew the speed.

00:05:58.092 --> 00:05:58.800
He knew the time.

00:05:58.800 --> 00:06:03.180
He said you're 40 years
overdue for a tsunami.

00:06:03.180 --> 00:06:05.040
He knew precisely the
one that would come.

00:06:05.040 --> 00:06:07.200
He was able to go and
look in the mountainsides

00:06:07.200 --> 00:06:10.200
above the Fukushima
Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant

00:06:10.200 --> 00:06:14.320
and find sand and stones that
came from this Jogan tsunami.

00:06:14.320 --> 00:06:16.590
Now, the problem with the
tsunami he foretold was it

00:06:16.590 --> 00:06:18.060
was from AD 869.

00:06:18.060 --> 00:06:19.650
It was a long time ago.

00:06:19.650 --> 00:06:21.840
So he would go to hearing
after hearing, a noted

00:06:21.840 --> 00:06:25.350
PhD seismologist from a
noted center of seismology,

00:06:25.350 --> 00:06:28.110
and warn them, do not build this
plant where you're building it.

00:06:28.110 --> 00:06:29.651
And every time he
would show up, they

00:06:29.651 --> 00:06:31.770
would say, Dr. Okamura,
thanks for coming.

00:06:31.770 --> 00:06:35.089
The hearing today is about
earthquakes, not tsunamis.

00:06:35.089 --> 00:06:36.630
Well, when's the
meeting on tsunamis?

00:06:36.630 --> 00:06:37.467
We don't know yet.

00:06:37.467 --> 00:06:39.300
The meeting on tsunamis
was never scheduled.

00:06:39.300 --> 00:06:42.420
He never was able
to be listened to.

00:06:42.420 --> 00:06:44.910
He was ignored repeatedly.

00:06:44.910 --> 00:06:48.450
So what happened because of
his warning not being heard?

00:06:48.450 --> 00:06:52.620
Well, the tsunami wave
showed up at the precise wave

00:06:52.620 --> 00:06:55.410
height he warned, about the same
time he said it would happen.

00:06:55.410 --> 00:06:59.430
It rushed in shore at 435 miles
an hour, crested the wall,

00:06:59.430 --> 00:07:01.680
and destroyed all the
backup power at Fukushima,

00:07:01.680 --> 00:07:06.440
leading to the largest nuclear
disaster since Chernobyl.

00:07:06.440 --> 00:07:09.870
19,000 people died in
Japan, and many of them

00:07:09.870 --> 00:07:12.990
tragically died when they
went to tsunami evacuation

00:07:12.990 --> 00:07:14.760
spots that were too low.

00:07:14.760 --> 00:07:16.470
Even the tsunami
evacuation spots

00:07:16.470 --> 00:07:19.080
hadn't been built to
the proper height.

00:07:19.080 --> 00:07:21.450
And Fukushima, what happens
when a nuclear power

00:07:21.450 --> 00:07:23.040
plant has no power?

00:07:23.040 --> 00:07:23.910
It melts down.

00:07:23.910 --> 00:07:24.660
It explodes.

00:07:24.660 --> 00:07:27.000
It spews toxic and
radioactive gases,

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:28.680
and that's what happened here.

00:07:28.680 --> 00:07:33.000
We estimate that if TEPCO, the
builder of the Fukushima plant,

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:35.700
had spent the money making
the improvements that Dr.

00:07:35.700 --> 00:07:39.300
Okamura had suggested, it would
have cost them $50 million.

00:07:39.300 --> 00:07:40.410
It's a real number.

00:07:40.410 --> 00:07:44.310
But it's cost $100 billion to
clean up the nuclear disaster.

00:07:44.310 --> 00:07:46.230
It will probably
lead to 10,000 deaths

00:07:46.230 --> 00:07:50.010
from the ongoing radiation
poisoning and cancers.

00:07:50.010 --> 00:07:54.360
That's a 2,000 times
return on the investment.

00:07:54.360 --> 00:07:56.040
Those examples and
many others were

00:07:56.040 --> 00:07:58.530
predicted in nearly
perfect detail

00:07:58.530 --> 00:08:01.110
by highly credible
data-driven experts,

00:08:01.110 --> 00:08:03.360
yet we ignored them,
one after the other.

00:08:03.360 --> 00:08:05.134
And we continue to do this.

00:08:05.134 --> 00:08:07.050
So the only question
that Dick and I could ask

00:08:07.050 --> 00:08:08.508
is, what the hell
is wrong with us?

00:08:08.508 --> 00:08:10.050
Why are we doing this wrong?

00:08:10.050 --> 00:08:11.464
Why don't we get this?

00:08:11.464 --> 00:08:13.380
Every one of these experts
had massive numbers

00:08:13.380 --> 00:08:15.010
of similarities.

00:08:15.010 --> 00:08:17.759
So we realized there
was a clear pattern

00:08:17.759 --> 00:08:18.800
through these interviews.

00:08:18.800 --> 00:08:20.341
One thing that was
pretty fascinating

00:08:20.341 --> 00:08:24.200
is they all said to
us two sentences.

00:08:24.200 --> 00:08:27.240
Every Cassandra we interviewed
said two things to us.

00:08:27.240 --> 00:08:30.890
One was, when I discovered
this data, when I figured out

00:08:30.890 --> 00:08:33.580
what was happening,
I wanted to be wrong.

00:08:33.580 --> 00:08:36.080
So I went to my colleagues and
said, please look at my data.

00:08:36.080 --> 00:08:37.789
Please study what
I think I found.

00:08:37.789 --> 00:08:39.243
Tell me this is inaccurate.

00:08:39.243 --> 00:08:41.659
And of course, in all instances
their colleagues couldn't.

00:08:41.659 --> 00:08:43.075
And the second
thing they all said

00:08:43.075 --> 00:08:45.350
was, well, now that
I knew it was right,

00:08:45.350 --> 00:08:48.815
I took it to the decision
makers and presumed

00:08:48.815 --> 00:08:49.690
they would act on it.

00:08:49.690 --> 00:08:51.620
And of course, they
didn't, or else they

00:08:51.620 --> 00:08:53.212
wouldn't be Cassandras.

00:08:53.212 --> 00:08:54.920
And when they ignored
it, I said to them,

00:08:54.920 --> 00:08:57.730
why are you ignoring
your own data?

00:08:57.730 --> 00:08:59.600
This wasn't proprietary insight.

00:08:59.600 --> 00:09:02.396
This was publicly available
data that they provided.

00:09:02.396 --> 00:09:04.020
So that's one thing
they had in common.

00:09:04.020 --> 00:09:07.500
Another thing we realized
they had in common

00:09:07.500 --> 00:09:10.050
was that there were four
sets of characteristics

00:09:10.050 --> 00:09:11.670
across every Cassandra event.

00:09:11.670 --> 00:09:14.100
We called this the
Cassandra Coefficient.

00:09:14.100 --> 00:09:16.570
The first one is
the warning itself.

00:09:16.570 --> 00:09:18.030
The second is the
decision makers,

00:09:18.030 --> 00:09:20.610
the third the Cassandra,
and the fourth the critics.

00:09:20.610 --> 00:09:22.410
Each one of those
things can help

00:09:22.410 --> 00:09:27.360
us identify if a warner is a
Chicken Little or a Cassandra.

00:09:27.360 --> 00:09:30.130
Now, this Cassandra Coefficient
is only the beginning.

00:09:30.130 --> 00:09:33.090
This book is very clear in
describing itself not as

00:09:33.090 --> 00:09:34.980
a perfectly scientific tome.

00:09:34.980 --> 00:09:37.170
There's a team at MIT
working on that now,

00:09:37.170 --> 00:09:38.880
doing a series of
analyses to figure out

00:09:38.880 --> 00:09:41.730
how to make this Cassandra
Coefficient more accurate.

00:09:41.730 --> 00:09:44.500
And I hope someone else
will look at that as well.

00:09:44.500 --> 00:09:48.030
But there are some very powerful
patterns that we found in here.

00:09:48.030 --> 00:09:52.890
I will mention only two of the
24 Cassandra Coefficients, two

00:09:52.890 --> 00:09:55.580
that we think are
relatively interesting.

00:09:55.580 --> 00:09:58.960
The first one is called
initial occurrence syndrome.

00:09:58.960 --> 00:10:03.850
Many of these disasters occurred
and nothing like it had ever--

00:10:03.850 --> 00:10:06.389
never occurred before.

00:10:06.389 --> 00:10:07.930
Initial occurrence
syndrome has to do

00:10:07.930 --> 00:10:11.620
with our human bias availability
heuristic and normalcy bias.

00:10:11.620 --> 00:10:14.110
It's very hard for us to
imagine something happening that

00:10:14.110 --> 00:10:16.030
hasn't happened
before, very difficult

00:10:16.030 --> 00:10:19.780
for us to see totally
novel events in our head.

00:10:19.780 --> 00:10:22.000
This is a quote by
Chairman Ben Bernanke, one

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:25.450
of the most intelligent men ever
to serve in the US government,

00:10:25.450 --> 00:10:27.430
highly credentialed,
highly smart.

00:10:27.430 --> 00:10:29.530
And in this instance,
he falls fully victim

00:10:29.530 --> 00:10:30.980
to initial occurrence syndrome.

00:10:30.980 --> 00:10:32.560
What he's saying
here is, we've never

00:10:32.560 --> 00:10:35.650
had the entire nation have a
real estate decline in prices.

00:10:35.650 --> 00:10:37.360
And since we haven't, we won't.

00:10:37.360 --> 00:10:40.210
And since we won't, we won't
have a full employment problem

00:10:40.210 --> 00:10:41.330
or an economic downturn.

00:10:41.330 --> 00:10:43.480
He said that in July 2005.

00:10:43.480 --> 00:10:46.220
When you see words
like "never before,"

00:10:46.220 --> 00:10:48.820
you should look twice and wonder
why people are thinking this.

00:10:48.820 --> 00:10:49.469
Was he right?

00:10:49.469 --> 00:10:51.010
Of course, he was
dramatically wrong.

00:10:51.010 --> 00:10:53.470
The 2008 collapse
happened entirely

00:10:53.470 --> 00:10:56.420
because of a nationwide
collapse in real estate.

00:10:56.420 --> 00:10:59.690
The 2008 collapse is also
notable for another Cassandra.

00:10:59.690 --> 00:11:03.380
Meredith Whitney, a young
Wall Street analyst,

00:11:03.380 --> 00:11:05.990
began to do the homework
on Citibank very early

00:11:05.990 --> 00:11:09.770
on in '06, '07, and realized
that they were going to fail

00:11:09.770 --> 00:11:10.700
as a company.

00:11:10.700 --> 00:11:15.499
The largest firm in the
world was going to collapse.

00:11:15.499 --> 00:11:16.540
Meredith had the numbers.

00:11:16.540 --> 00:11:17.650
She had the data.

00:11:17.650 --> 00:11:19.300
She produced her estimate.

00:11:19.300 --> 00:11:20.410
She was obviously right.

00:11:20.410 --> 00:11:22.810
But until she was right,
what did she get in return?

00:11:22.810 --> 00:11:26.080
Death threats, threats of being
fired, and extraordinarily

00:11:26.080 --> 00:11:28.000
sexist responses.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:30.790
She then was correct about
Lehman and then Bear.

00:11:30.790 --> 00:11:33.040
In every instance, she
was ahead of the market.

00:11:33.040 --> 00:11:34.410
She was ahead of the naysayers.

00:11:34.410 --> 00:11:35.590
This Cassandra was correct.

00:11:38.600 --> 00:11:42.710
The other major category
of why we get things wrong

00:11:42.710 --> 00:11:44.886
has to do with not
so much our biases--

00:11:44.886 --> 00:11:46.760
and if you look at the
Cassandra Coefficient,

00:11:46.760 --> 00:11:49.093
there's a large number of
things that are highly related

00:11:49.093 --> 00:11:50.546
to human biases.

00:11:50.546 --> 00:11:52.670
The other one has to do
with the massive complexity

00:11:52.670 --> 00:11:54.670
in the world.

00:11:54.670 --> 00:11:57.570
I call this the
acceleration of history.

00:11:57.570 --> 00:11:59.810
We were all taught how
the Second Industrial

00:11:59.810 --> 00:12:02.666
Revolution of 1870
led to World War

00:12:02.666 --> 00:12:04.220
I which led to World War II.

00:12:04.220 --> 00:12:06.680
When you have
technological revolutions,

00:12:06.680 --> 00:12:08.390
you end up with
massive displacements.

00:12:08.390 --> 00:12:10.380
Yes, you have winners,
but for all the winners,

00:12:10.380 --> 00:12:11.720
you have losers.

00:12:11.720 --> 00:12:15.470
The losers often tend to be the
employed class, the blue collar

00:12:15.470 --> 00:12:18.410
class, as it has been in
every technological revolution

00:12:18.410 --> 00:12:21.052
that we've had
throughout history.

00:12:21.052 --> 00:12:23.010
And when you have a large
number of unemployed,

00:12:23.010 --> 00:12:26.640
you obviously have a massive
disruption to society.

00:12:26.640 --> 00:12:28.680
The 1870 technological
revolution

00:12:28.680 --> 00:12:30.942
led to World War I,
led to World War II.

00:12:30.942 --> 00:12:32.400
And other technological
revolutions

00:12:32.400 --> 00:12:33.910
have been just as disruptive.

00:12:33.910 --> 00:12:35.790
Now, as you look
at this chart, you

00:12:35.790 --> 00:12:39.720
see the periodicity between the
revolutions is getting shorter.

00:12:39.720 --> 00:12:42.440
We go from 200 years
till 1780, to 100 years

00:12:42.440 --> 00:12:45.220
till 1870, and on we go.

00:12:45.220 --> 00:12:46.890
The periodicity matters.

00:12:46.890 --> 00:12:50.280
Society needs time to absorb
and retrain the workers.

00:12:50.280 --> 00:12:53.220
We need time to get back
on our feet as nations.

00:12:53.220 --> 00:12:54.600
We need time to
get over the wars

00:12:54.600 --> 00:12:57.060
that we generally have had
after these revolutions.

00:12:57.060 --> 00:13:00.780
But the periodicity between
the technological revolutions

00:13:00.780 --> 00:13:06.100
is getting much, much closer
together, much shorter.

00:13:06.100 --> 00:13:08.420
How fast are we
moving as a society?

00:13:08.420 --> 00:13:10.360
How fast is history
accelerating?

00:13:10.360 --> 00:13:12.580
Well, it's worth noting
the period of time

00:13:12.580 --> 00:13:15.310
from the bronze
sword to the steel

00:13:15.310 --> 00:13:19.240
sword is four times longer than
the time from the steel sword

00:13:19.240 --> 00:13:20.910
to the nuclear weapon.

00:13:20.910 --> 00:13:23.980
We are moving
extraordinarily quickly.

00:13:23.980 --> 00:13:26.830
Now, if you look at where
we find ourselves today,

00:13:26.830 --> 00:13:29.350
you could argue we have three
technological revolutions

00:13:29.350 --> 00:13:31.960
happening at the same time--

00:13:31.960 --> 00:13:34.480
three revolutions that are
leading to massive disruption,

00:13:34.480 --> 00:13:36.532
three revolutions that
are changing regions,

00:13:36.532 --> 00:13:37.990
three revolutions
that are changing

00:13:37.990 --> 00:13:40.030
employment and employability.

00:13:40.030 --> 00:13:42.520
They're all happening within
a decade of each other.

00:13:42.520 --> 00:13:44.800
Super intelligence and
artificial intelligence,

00:13:44.800 --> 00:13:47.730
genetics, and energy.

00:13:47.730 --> 00:13:50.160
It is this complexity
mismatch, it's

00:13:50.160 --> 00:13:52.170
this acceleration
of history that

00:13:52.170 --> 00:13:54.150
also makes it hard
for decision makers

00:13:54.150 --> 00:13:57.470
to make decisions
when given warnings.

00:13:57.470 --> 00:14:00.500
I'll give you an example
of complexity mismatch.

00:14:00.500 --> 00:14:02.460
Harry Markopolos is a quant.

00:14:02.460 --> 00:14:05.670
Harry Markopolos is a very,
very smart hedge fund manager,

00:14:05.670 --> 00:14:08.630
and Harry Markopolos got a
warning of a hedge fund run

00:14:08.630 --> 00:14:10.400
by a guy named Bernie Madoff.

00:14:10.400 --> 00:14:12.620
When Harry began to look
at the Madoff hedge fund,

00:14:12.620 --> 00:14:16.130
he said he realized within five
minutes it was a Ponzi scheme.

00:14:16.130 --> 00:14:17.210
How did he know?

00:14:17.210 --> 00:14:18.620
The math told him so.

00:14:18.620 --> 00:14:19.940
The data told him so.

00:14:19.940 --> 00:14:22.010
His education told him so.

00:14:22.010 --> 00:14:22.890
So what did he do?

00:14:22.890 --> 00:14:24.830
He went to his friends and said,
this can't be right, can it?

00:14:24.830 --> 00:14:25.541
They said it is.

00:14:25.541 --> 00:14:28.040
He went to the SEC and said,
please listen to me, won't you?

00:14:28.040 --> 00:14:28.730
They said, no.

00:14:28.730 --> 00:14:30.770
He said, how are you
ignoring your own data?

00:14:30.770 --> 00:14:32.390
The exact same story.

00:14:32.390 --> 00:14:35.690
He had 11 exchanges with
the SEC over nine years.

00:14:35.690 --> 00:14:39.170
He provided three highly
complicated explanations

00:14:39.170 --> 00:14:41.140
of why Bernie
Madoff was a fraud.

00:14:41.140 --> 00:14:43.730
He was ignored every time.

00:14:43.730 --> 00:14:45.950
Do you remember when
the SEC arrested

00:14:45.950 --> 00:14:47.690
or caught Bernie Madoff?

00:14:47.690 --> 00:14:48.530
They didn't.

00:14:48.530 --> 00:14:50.480
Bernie Madoff's
kids turned him in.

00:14:50.480 --> 00:14:52.850
He went scot-free for decades.

00:14:52.850 --> 00:14:57.530
He stole $65 billion, the
largest financial fraud

00:14:57.530 --> 00:14:59.590
in history.

00:14:59.590 --> 00:15:04.050
And the warnings were
there, in perfect data.

00:15:04.050 --> 00:15:06.686
Complexity mismatch--
it's very hard for people

00:15:06.686 --> 00:15:07.810
to understand these things.

00:15:07.810 --> 00:15:10.620
Now remember, the lawyers
at the SEC at the time,

00:15:10.620 --> 00:15:11.780
well, they were lawyers.

00:15:11.780 --> 00:15:13.030
They were liberal arts grads.

00:15:13.030 --> 00:15:15.727
When Harry came in with a bunch
of charts and math and numbers,

00:15:15.727 --> 00:15:16.810
they didn't understand it.

00:15:16.810 --> 00:15:17.980
They couldn't get it.

00:15:17.980 --> 00:15:19.680
That's a relatively easy thing.

00:15:19.680 --> 00:15:22.180
Imagine how hard this is going
to be with superintelligence.

00:15:22.180 --> 00:15:24.110
Imagine how hard this is
going to be with the nano.

00:15:24.110 --> 00:15:26.651
Imagine a how this is going to
be with new sources of energy,

00:15:26.651 --> 00:15:28.120
genetics, CRISPR.

00:15:28.120 --> 00:15:30.100
We're in real trouble
if we can't begin

00:15:30.100 --> 00:15:33.040
to understand what's going on.

00:15:33.040 --> 00:15:34.746
So while that's an
historical look back,

00:15:34.746 --> 00:15:36.120
the only value to
this book would

00:15:36.120 --> 00:15:37.703
be if we can see
something coming down

00:15:37.703 --> 00:15:38.970
the pike in the future.

00:15:38.970 --> 00:15:40.980
Can we apply the
Cassandra Coefficient

00:15:40.980 --> 00:15:42.690
to current warnings?

00:15:42.690 --> 00:15:44.880
At the end of the book,
the final seven chapters,

00:15:44.880 --> 00:15:47.254
we looked at seven
other threats.

00:15:47.254 --> 00:15:49.170
These are people right
now pounding the table,

00:15:49.170 --> 00:15:50.880
warning us, explaining
to us that these

00:15:50.880 --> 00:15:53.400
are species-level risks.

00:15:53.400 --> 00:15:54.580
Things that could kill.

00:15:54.580 --> 00:15:56.663
There's a phrase that I
learned writing this book,

00:15:56.663 --> 00:15:59.880
a word called gigadeath,
billions of people killed.

00:15:59.880 --> 00:16:01.740
People who traffic in
this world understand

00:16:01.740 --> 00:16:02.641
these horrible ideas.

00:16:02.641 --> 00:16:04.890
It's very difficult for us
to get our heads around it.

00:16:04.890 --> 00:16:06.234
That's what they think about.

00:16:06.234 --> 00:16:08.400
When we wrote this book
about a year and a half ago,

00:16:08.400 --> 00:16:11.340
the actual drafting, all
seven of these warnings

00:16:11.340 --> 00:16:13.730
seemed a little preposterous,
a little out there.

00:16:13.730 --> 00:16:17.910
In a year since then, five
of them-- six of them--

00:16:17.910 --> 00:16:22.114
five of them, they've gone
from fantastic to probable.

00:16:22.114 --> 00:16:23.280
I'm going to talk about two.

00:16:26.900 --> 00:16:28.550
The first one is very timely.

00:16:28.550 --> 00:16:30.700
This is a warning being
given to us right now

00:16:30.700 --> 00:16:33.460
by a noted professor
named Alan Robock.

00:16:33.460 --> 00:16:36.730
Alan has picked up the work
previously done by Carl Sagan.

00:16:36.730 --> 00:16:40.060
Carl Sagan, in the '70s
and '80s, very ingeniously

00:16:40.060 --> 00:16:42.430
teamed with a group
of Russian scientists

00:16:42.430 --> 00:16:44.230
and did a lot of
study about what

00:16:44.230 --> 00:16:46.152
would happen if 1,000
nuclear weapons were

00:16:46.152 --> 00:16:48.610
thrown back and forth between
the United States and Russia.

00:16:48.610 --> 00:16:50.830
Other than the death,
other than the destruction,

00:16:50.830 --> 00:16:53.230
what would occur to the planet?

00:16:53.230 --> 00:16:55.510
What he discovered is
you'd have massive fires.

00:16:55.510 --> 00:16:57.600
Those fires would create
superheated plumes.

00:16:57.600 --> 00:16:59.300
The plumes would go
in the mesosphere.

00:16:59.300 --> 00:17:01.300
And they would dump a
huge degree of effectively

00:17:01.300 --> 00:17:03.550
dust and small particulate
matter around the earth.

00:17:03.550 --> 00:17:07.540
That leads to global
nuclear winter.

00:17:07.540 --> 00:17:10.869
Global nuclear winter
was considered so proven,

00:17:10.869 --> 00:17:14.230
so mathematically
correct, so well-modeled

00:17:14.230 --> 00:17:16.119
by the Russians
and the Americans

00:17:16.119 --> 00:17:19.599
that Carl Sagan's theory led
to a huge degree of disarmament

00:17:19.599 --> 00:17:21.670
talks, disarmament success.

00:17:21.670 --> 00:17:25.030
It's considered a
really magical tool

00:17:25.030 --> 00:17:27.700
to help ease some of the
tensions in the Cold War.

00:17:27.700 --> 00:17:30.040
He was considered correct.

00:17:30.040 --> 00:17:32.050
Alan Robock, our
current Cassandra,

00:17:32.050 --> 00:17:34.490
went to go look at
Sagan's work using,

00:17:34.490 --> 00:17:37.356
obviously, much more advanced
computers, much larger models.

00:17:37.356 --> 00:17:38.480
And he said, wait a second.

00:17:38.480 --> 00:17:41.110
You don't just need thousands
of weapons going back and forth.

00:17:41.110 --> 00:17:43.193
You could probably trigger
a global nuclear winter

00:17:43.193 --> 00:17:44.770
with 40 weapons.

00:17:44.770 --> 00:17:47.110
Now, 40 seems like a lot of
nuclear weapons in a world

00:17:47.110 --> 00:17:48.460
when we've only used two.

00:17:48.460 --> 00:17:49.570
40 is not.

00:17:49.570 --> 00:17:52.472
I've worked on nuclear weapons
strategy, nuclear planning.

00:17:52.472 --> 00:17:54.430
When the United States
decides to hit a target,

00:17:54.430 --> 00:17:57.790
like perhaps North Korea,
it's 30 weapons minimum.

00:17:57.790 --> 00:18:00.260
That's just our weapons.

00:18:00.260 --> 00:18:03.772
Nuclear weapons don't go in
onesies and twosies anymore.

00:18:03.772 --> 00:18:05.230
So Alan Robock took
a look at this.

00:18:05.230 --> 00:18:08.520
And his initial study was
on Pakistan and India.

00:18:08.520 --> 00:18:11.890
And he came back and said
that if they went to war,

00:18:11.890 --> 00:18:12.640
we'd have trouble.

00:18:12.640 --> 00:18:17.700
And he's since modeled a Korean
peninsula nuclear exchange.

00:18:17.700 --> 00:18:22.389
What he's found is if even 40
warheads are shared in between,

00:18:22.389 --> 00:18:24.180
this would trigger a
global nuclear winter,

00:18:24.180 --> 00:18:27.075
where the entire earth
temperature would go down two

00:18:27.075 --> 00:18:28.680
to four degrees Fahrenheit.

00:18:28.680 --> 00:18:31.750
Crop productions would
go down 15% to 25%.

00:18:31.750 --> 00:18:35.610
And that would lead to 1
to 2 billion people dead.

00:18:35.610 --> 00:18:37.560
So while 40 weapons
in the peninsula

00:18:37.560 --> 00:18:39.390
would be a horrific
thing in and of itself,

00:18:39.390 --> 00:18:41.430
it could lead to a
global catastrophe

00:18:41.430 --> 00:18:42.960
like we can't imagine.

00:18:42.960 --> 00:18:46.560
This is hard science, real
data, by an eminently qualified

00:18:46.560 --> 00:18:49.050
expert who's trying to
get the word out there.

00:18:49.050 --> 00:18:50.610
Now, the good news
is Alan Robock

00:18:50.610 --> 00:18:52.985
and his team won the Nobel
Prize last year for their work

00:18:52.985 --> 00:18:54.330
on nuclear weapons disarmament.

00:18:54.330 --> 00:18:56.940
His work on weapons disarmament
is being well heard.

00:18:56.940 --> 00:19:00.540
His work on global nuclear
weapons theory is not.

00:19:00.540 --> 00:19:03.660
I've had conversations with
the parts of the US government

00:19:03.660 --> 00:19:05.580
that are making the
nuclear weapons plans that

00:19:05.580 --> 00:19:08.220
would be the ones who would
actually press the button,

00:19:08.220 --> 00:19:11.950
and this theory is
largely unknown to them.

00:19:11.950 --> 00:19:15.100
That's a real problem.

00:19:15.100 --> 00:19:17.520
The final risk I
want to talk about

00:19:17.520 --> 00:19:21.810
is about artificial intelligence
and then superintelligence.

00:19:21.810 --> 00:19:23.806
Artificial intelligence,
meaning machines

00:19:23.806 --> 00:19:25.680
that do the work of
humans, is all around us.

00:19:25.680 --> 00:19:26.917
It's your ATM machine.

00:19:26.917 --> 00:19:29.250
If you don't think you're
already a cybernetic organism,

00:19:29.250 --> 00:19:31.624
try to survive without your
phone or computer for a week.

00:19:31.624 --> 00:19:32.460
You are.

00:19:32.460 --> 00:19:34.810
Superintelligence is
dramatically different.

00:19:34.810 --> 00:19:37.320
It's the idea that a computer
can be, quote, unquote,

00:19:37.320 --> 00:19:39.600
"smarter than a human"
at all tasks humans do.

00:19:39.600 --> 00:19:42.390
It's also called AGI,
artificial general intelligence.

00:19:42.390 --> 00:19:46.290
I'll call it superintelligence
to make it easy to understand.

00:19:46.290 --> 00:19:50.010
It is definitionally very
hard for our small brains

00:19:50.010 --> 00:19:52.800
to understand a thing that would
be twice as smart, 10 times as

00:19:52.800 --> 00:19:56.190
smart, or 1,000
times as smart as us.

00:19:56.190 --> 00:19:59.310
But please understand
there is no real argument

00:19:59.310 --> 00:20:00.600
that this is coming.

00:20:00.600 --> 00:20:03.330
Every person involved with
superintelligence or artificial

00:20:03.330 --> 00:20:06.090
intelligence, down to
only a couple dissenters,

00:20:06.090 --> 00:20:09.340
says yes, we will get
to superintelligence.

00:20:09.340 --> 00:20:11.860
Now, we don't know the how
and we don't know the when.

00:20:11.860 --> 00:20:13.901
That makes it very difficult
to make the argument

00:20:13.901 --> 00:20:16.870
that we should be concerned
about it, but it is coming.

00:20:16.870 --> 00:20:19.447
In fact, when it does come,
it'll come very quickly.

00:20:19.447 --> 00:20:21.655
We're talking about machines
that program themselves.

00:20:21.655 --> 00:20:24.280
It's called self-recursive
programming.

00:20:24.280 --> 00:20:26.800
This is a self-replicating
technology.

00:20:26.800 --> 00:20:28.870
A little footnote--
any technology

00:20:28.870 --> 00:20:33.820
that's self-replicating or
self-recursive and asymmetric

00:20:33.820 --> 00:20:35.980
is wildly dangerous.

00:20:35.980 --> 00:20:38.140
This is a self-replicating
technology.

00:20:38.140 --> 00:20:42.594
It has to be considered
extraordinarily powerful.

00:20:42.594 --> 00:20:45.010
The only argument about this
superintelligence, as I said,

00:20:45.010 --> 00:20:46.330
isn't if it will happen or not.

00:20:46.330 --> 00:20:49.690
It's if it will bring
good tidings or bad.

00:20:49.690 --> 00:20:51.970
We spent some time
with Eli Yudkowsky.

00:20:51.970 --> 00:20:53.940
He's our Cassandra in
this part of the book.

00:20:53.940 --> 00:20:55.900
He's a man of
extraordinary intellect

00:20:55.900 --> 00:20:59.260
and now of great stature who
is dedicating his entire life

00:20:59.260 --> 00:21:01.630
to ensuring that
superintelligence is safe,

00:21:01.630 --> 00:21:03.010
that it brings good tidings.

00:21:03.010 --> 00:21:04.540
It's a very difficult puzzle.

00:21:04.540 --> 00:21:07.030
He doesn't know the solution
yet, but he's dedicated to it.

00:21:07.030 --> 00:21:08.890
And in fact,
billions of dollars,

00:21:08.890 --> 00:21:10.510
nominally, are
being dedicated now

00:21:10.510 --> 00:21:12.820
towards ensuring that
superintelligence

00:21:12.820 --> 00:21:15.460
is done safely.

00:21:15.460 --> 00:21:20.650
Elon Musk, Stephen Hawking,
Bill Gates, Eli Yudkowsky,

00:21:20.650 --> 00:21:23.350
philosopher Nick Bostrom, who
I think gave a Google Talk,

00:21:23.350 --> 00:21:25.690
they all say, you
better watch out.

00:21:25.690 --> 00:21:28.780
This is a species-level
event of extraordinary risk.

00:21:28.780 --> 00:21:32.520
Others aren't so concerned.

00:21:32.520 --> 00:21:35.340
There's two possible
outcomes, to make it simple,

00:21:35.340 --> 00:21:36.960
with superintelligence.

00:21:36.960 --> 00:21:39.750
One is personified here
by this picture of Lobot

00:21:39.750 --> 00:21:40.900
from "Star Wars."

00:21:40.900 --> 00:21:43.704
Lobot, as you can see with his
1970s technology in his face

00:21:43.704 --> 00:21:45.870
looks-- he looks like an
Atari console or something.

00:21:45.870 --> 00:21:50.440
But Lobot is a
cybernetic machine,

00:21:50.440 --> 00:21:53.990
part human, part computer.

00:21:53.990 --> 00:21:57.860
Google's own Ray Kurzweil
looks at this as the future

00:21:57.860 --> 00:21:58.760
of superintelligence.

00:21:58.760 --> 00:22:00.950
He tells a very
rosy story that we

00:22:00.950 --> 00:22:03.710
don't have to be concerned
about superintelligence

00:22:03.710 --> 00:22:05.690
because we will get the
cybernetic interface,

00:22:05.690 --> 00:22:09.830
and we'll be able to learn
with, grow with, and control

00:22:09.830 --> 00:22:14.550
superintelligence because of
our capacity to be part of it.

00:22:14.550 --> 00:22:16.430
He and others argue,
the Lobot argument,

00:22:16.430 --> 00:22:17.990
that superintelligence
will create

00:22:17.990 --> 00:22:19.640
an immense amount of good.

00:22:19.640 --> 00:22:20.510
And it will.

00:22:20.510 --> 00:22:22.800
This is the most powerful
tool of all time.

00:22:22.800 --> 00:22:25.700
Any problem that can be solved
by computation or intelligence

00:22:25.700 --> 00:22:28.670
will be solved by
superintelligence.

00:22:28.670 --> 00:22:30.290
Problems we don't
know exist will

00:22:30.290 --> 00:22:31.820
be solved by superintelligence.

00:22:31.820 --> 00:22:32.570
That means hunger.

00:22:32.570 --> 00:22:33.422
That means disease.

00:22:33.422 --> 00:22:34.130
That means death.

00:22:34.130 --> 00:22:35.510
That means climate change.

00:22:35.510 --> 00:22:38.090
This is the most powerful
tool ever to be invented.

00:22:38.090 --> 00:22:40.130
And remember, as I said,
it will be invented.

00:22:40.130 --> 00:22:42.300
There's no question of that.

00:22:42.300 --> 00:22:44.160
But it's been called
our final invention.

00:22:44.160 --> 00:22:46.950
It will then invent
everything else.

00:22:46.950 --> 00:22:49.090
And the question is,
yes, it will give us

00:22:49.090 --> 00:22:51.730
all those great societal
benefits as described,

00:22:51.730 --> 00:22:53.066
but what does it do then?

00:22:53.066 --> 00:22:54.940
So then you switch to
the other picture here.

00:22:54.940 --> 00:22:57.790
And this is of the
Terminator T-2000.

00:22:57.790 --> 00:22:59.800
And every conversation
on superintelligence

00:22:59.800 --> 00:23:01.870
apparently has to
show this picture.

00:23:01.870 --> 00:23:03.280
We've all watched this movie.

00:23:03.280 --> 00:23:06.310
We all know that robots
will come for us.

00:23:06.310 --> 00:23:10.480
Footnote-- part of the fact
that that is so outlandish, part

00:23:10.480 --> 00:23:13.330
of the fact that Hollywood
has peppered us with movies

00:23:13.330 --> 00:23:15.050
about robots coming
to get us makes

00:23:15.050 --> 00:23:16.550
us believe it's not
going to happen.

00:23:16.550 --> 00:23:18.924
It makes us believe it's in
the realm of fantasy in film,

00:23:18.924 --> 00:23:20.440
not in our actual lives.

00:23:20.440 --> 00:23:23.280
It's inured us to the threat.

00:23:23.280 --> 00:23:25.050
People like Gates and
Hawking and others

00:23:25.050 --> 00:23:27.390
believe this is a real risk.

00:23:27.390 --> 00:23:31.087
And this is the way we'll
personify it in this instance.

00:23:31.087 --> 00:23:32.920
The only way I could
basically describe this

00:23:32.920 --> 00:23:36.270
is think about a genie
coming out of the bottle.

00:23:36.270 --> 00:23:38.362
In every narrative, it
gives you three wishes.

00:23:38.362 --> 00:23:39.820
I described the
goodness that we'll

00:23:39.820 --> 00:23:40.945
get from superintelligence.

00:23:40.945 --> 00:23:43.680
But then the genie is
off to do its own thing.

00:23:43.680 --> 00:23:46.080
Now, I don't know if we'll
control superintelligence.

00:23:46.080 --> 00:23:48.760
I don't know if Eli
Yudkowsky will be right

00:23:48.760 --> 00:23:54.570
and if we can put ethics
into the computer.

00:23:54.570 --> 00:23:57.770
I have a really hard time
understanding how we will.

00:23:57.770 --> 00:24:01.720
But I know it's a question
we have to address.

00:24:01.720 --> 00:24:04.180
Elon Musk calls this
summoning the demon.

00:24:04.180 --> 00:24:06.280
And the one question
people often ask is, well,

00:24:06.280 --> 00:24:07.660
can't you just turn it off?

00:24:07.660 --> 00:24:10.650
Well, why didn't chimpanzees hit
the off switch on human beings?

00:24:15.740 --> 00:24:17.960
Again, every noted
expert working

00:24:17.960 --> 00:24:19.460
on artificial
intelligence agrees

00:24:19.460 --> 00:24:21.950
we will have superintelligence
at some point, probably

00:24:21.950 --> 00:24:23.240
within the next 100 years.

00:24:23.240 --> 00:24:25.680
I would guess 25 years.

00:24:25.680 --> 00:24:29.630
This is a photo of
the World GO champion

00:24:29.630 --> 00:24:33.090
losing to your computer here
at Google called AlphaGo.

00:24:33.090 --> 00:24:35.192
And if you want to see
the face of dejection,

00:24:35.192 --> 00:24:36.650
I think you can
see it right there.

00:24:39.760 --> 00:24:41.930
This chess-- this
GO tournament was

00:24:41.930 --> 00:24:44.790
watched by a huge number
of people inside Asia.

00:24:44.790 --> 00:24:46.550
It was a massive event.

00:24:46.550 --> 00:24:48.680
It was a massive event
for popular media,

00:24:48.680 --> 00:24:51.230
but it also was a massive
event in the superintelligence

00:24:51.230 --> 00:24:52.040
community.

00:24:52.040 --> 00:24:54.110
I called up and talked
to one of the experts

00:24:54.110 --> 00:24:55.580
we had worked with
on this chapter

00:24:55.580 --> 00:24:58.522
as soon as this win had
happened, and I said,

00:24:58.522 --> 00:25:00.980
you told me that this wasn't
going to happen in five years.

00:25:00.980 --> 00:25:03.030
And he said, I thought it wasn't
going to happen in five years.

00:25:03.030 --> 00:25:04.250
And he was almost in tears.

00:25:04.250 --> 00:25:06.290
It's not supposed to have
happened this quickly.

00:25:06.290 --> 00:25:08.870
Technology develops much faster
than humans usually give it

00:25:08.870 --> 00:25:11.130
credit to be able to do.

00:25:11.130 --> 00:25:13.390
We are very, very bad as
a race of understanding

00:25:13.390 --> 00:25:16.520
technological development.

00:25:16.520 --> 00:25:18.690
Complexity mismatch,
which I mentioned before,

00:25:18.690 --> 00:25:20.700
is all over the issue
of superintelligence.

00:25:20.700 --> 00:25:22.710
We do not understand
what's happening here.

00:25:22.710 --> 00:25:24.960
Another issue called
diffusion of responsibility

00:25:24.960 --> 00:25:26.926
is all over superintelligence.

00:25:26.926 --> 00:25:29.550
Can you tell me who at the White
House is responsible for this?

00:25:29.550 --> 00:25:31.020
Can you tell me who in
the Department of Defense

00:25:31.020 --> 00:25:32.400
is in charge of
making sure we don't

00:25:32.400 --> 00:25:34.200
get killed by
superintelligence and robots?

00:25:34.200 --> 00:25:36.030
I don't know who it is.

00:25:36.030 --> 00:25:40.620
But standing here, I believe
Eli Yudkowsky, Elon Musk, Bill

00:25:40.620 --> 00:25:43.389
Gates, Stephen Hawking
is giving us the chance

00:25:43.389 --> 00:25:44.430
to listen to a Cassandra.

00:25:44.430 --> 00:25:46.600
This is a Cassandra moment.

00:25:46.600 --> 00:25:49.200
And if I, at the Google
campus, didn't mention this,

00:25:49.200 --> 00:25:50.430
I'd be remiss.

00:25:50.430 --> 00:25:53.160
You are one of two or
three places in the world

00:25:53.160 --> 00:25:56.610
legitimately in the race to
create superintelligence.

00:25:56.610 --> 00:25:59.987
Google may well have the fate
of humanity in its hands.

00:25:59.987 --> 00:26:01.320
It's an extraordinary statement.

00:26:01.320 --> 00:26:03.611
What other company in history
could you say that about?

00:26:06.390 --> 00:26:08.280
Google's leaders,
in some instances,

00:26:08.280 --> 00:26:11.670
have become dismissive about
the threat of superintelligence.

00:26:11.670 --> 00:26:13.200
That worries me.

00:26:13.200 --> 00:26:17.190
Google's early manifesto
was, don't be evil.

00:26:17.190 --> 00:26:22.380
Google's new manifesto needs
to be, don't build evil.

00:26:25.360 --> 00:26:28.460
Cassandras are out there,
and we need to find them.

00:26:28.460 --> 00:26:31.410
We now have a tool
to help us do so.

00:26:31.410 --> 00:26:33.680
And I think we can do a
much better job at this.

00:26:33.680 --> 00:26:36.290
So Dick and I have
dedicated a huge amount

00:26:36.290 --> 00:26:39.110
of our future effort to getting
the word out about Cassandras.

00:26:39.110 --> 00:26:41.240
This wasn't about writing
a book or making money.

00:26:41.240 --> 00:26:42.840
There's no money
in books anymore.

00:26:42.840 --> 00:26:44.760
This was about
getting a message out

00:26:44.760 --> 00:26:47.750
so others don't have to feel
the dejection and the failure

00:26:47.750 --> 00:26:51.580
and the catastrophe of giving
a warning and being ignored.

00:26:51.580 --> 00:26:54.250
We've created something called
the Cassandra Award Foundation.

00:26:54.250 --> 00:26:56.260
You can see the board
and jury up here.

00:26:56.260 --> 00:26:57.730
Some very distinguished
individuals

00:26:57.730 --> 00:27:01.680
have joined us, including
some former Cassandras.

00:27:01.680 --> 00:27:03.430
We have representatives
from the military,

00:27:03.430 --> 00:27:07.600
from intelligence, from
Wall Street, from medicine.

00:27:07.600 --> 00:27:10.540
And we, every year,
will give out one award

00:27:10.540 --> 00:27:12.790
to one individual giving
a warning we think needs

00:27:12.790 --> 00:27:15.400
more attention.

00:27:15.400 --> 00:27:18.220
We gave the award this
year to Alan Robock.

00:27:18.220 --> 00:27:20.830
I mentioned earlier Alan's
work on global climate change,

00:27:20.830 --> 00:27:22.720
on a new nuclear winter.

00:27:22.720 --> 00:27:24.880
We gave him the Cassandra Award.

00:27:24.880 --> 00:27:26.950
And part of the value
here isn't that he

00:27:26.950 --> 00:27:29.350
gets to hold a piece of
glass, as pretty as it is.

00:27:29.350 --> 00:27:31.990
Part of the value is
that Alan's work ideally

00:27:31.990 --> 00:27:33.400
gets a little more of a voice.

00:27:33.400 --> 00:27:35.440
More people pay attention
to what he was doing.

00:27:35.440 --> 00:27:36.700
The members of the board--

00:27:36.700 --> 00:27:38.080
you saw their names earlier--

00:27:38.080 --> 00:27:40.570
we've all committed to
trying to get the story out.

00:27:40.570 --> 00:27:42.906
When we go on media now,
we talk about Alan Robock.

00:27:42.906 --> 00:27:44.530
When we meet with
government officials,

00:27:44.530 --> 00:27:47.080
we talk about Alan
Robock and the fear

00:27:47.080 --> 00:27:49.970
that we all have of a
global nuclear winter.

00:27:49.970 --> 00:27:52.060
We're going to give this
award out every year.

00:27:52.060 --> 00:27:53.740
It is a nonprofit organization.

00:27:53.740 --> 00:27:55.090
The website's on there.

00:27:55.090 --> 00:27:59.620
Please nominate others about
whom we have to be concerned.

00:27:59.620 --> 00:28:01.870
And please donate if
you're interested.

00:28:01.870 --> 00:28:05.650
The funds are used entirely
to reward the award winner

00:28:05.650 --> 00:28:08.560
and to pay for publicity
around the message.

00:28:08.560 --> 00:28:10.000
So thank you for
taking the time,

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:13.090
and please remember we've
found a tool we think

00:28:13.090 --> 00:28:15.880
can help us avert catastrophes.

