really, really lucky

00:43:01.210 --> 00:43:03.100
to have great colleagues
and bosses all the way

00:43:03.100 --> 00:43:03.725
along the line.

00:43:03.725 --> 00:43:05.309
Dick was really one
of my first bosses

00:43:05.309 --> 00:43:06.974
and has been
extraordinarily influential

00:43:06.974 --> 00:43:08.410
in my life, all
the way to today.

00:43:08.410 --> 00:43:09.730
He's godfather of
our third child.

00:43:09.730 --> 00:43:11.104
He was a groomsman
at my wedding.

00:43:11.104 --> 00:43:14.020
And I wouldn't be
anything of who

00:43:14.020 --> 00:43:16.240
I am if it weren't for all
of his time and influence

00:43:16.240 --> 00:43:19.270
and love, and I can't
thank him enough.

00:43:19.270 --> 00:43:21.320
And after I left
government, I got

00:43:21.320 --> 00:43:23.320
to work at some great
organizations, the Monitor

00:43:23.320 --> 00:43:26.500
Group with Mark Fuller, Gerson
Lehrman Group with Mark Gerson

00:43:26.500 --> 00:43:27.832
and Alexander Saint-Amand.

00:43:27.832 --> 00:43:29.290
And then from Gerson
Lehrman Group,

00:43:29.290 --> 00:43:31.460
I created Ergo with my
partners Matthew Moneyhon

00:43:31.460 --> 00:43:32.800
and Evan Pressman.

00:43:32.800 --> 00:43:36.690
And Ergo is now 14 years old.

00:43:36.690 --> 00:43:38.200
And we came out
of-- it really is

00:43:38.200 --> 00:43:39.670
a reflection of where we came.

00:43:39.670 --> 00:43:42.700
It's a reflection of diplomacy
and intelligence and research.

00:43:42.700 --> 00:43:44.470
And that's what Ergo
does, and that's

00:43:44.470 --> 00:43:46.850
where my partners
come from as well.

00:43:46.850 --> 00:43:49.290
And it's been a huge joy.

00:43:49.290 --> 00:43:51.517
And what we do at
Ergo is part of what

00:43:51.517 --> 00:43:52.600
we're talking about today.

00:43:52.600 --> 00:43:56.650
We try to give people frameworks
to understand the future.

00:43:56.650 --> 00:43:59.020
Now, this is a framework
to understand catastrophes.

00:43:59.020 --> 00:44:00.880
This framework works
on other things too.

00:44:00.880 --> 00:44:02.950
But there's only a
few proven frameworks

00:44:02.950 --> 00:44:05.050
about how to look
around corners--

00:44:05.050 --> 00:44:09.490
scenario planning, virtual
markets, Cassandra theory.

00:44:09.490 --> 00:44:12.101
So we try to bring those
frameworks to our clients.

00:44:12.101 --> 00:44:13.600
And we're a little
different in that

00:44:13.600 --> 00:44:18.790
we infuse our analysis almost
entirely with on the ground

00:44:18.790 --> 00:44:20.030
intelligence.

00:44:20.030 --> 00:44:23.740
So we've paid 36,000 people
for information in 14 years,

00:44:23.740 --> 00:44:26.200
all around the world,
people from shop floors

00:44:26.200 --> 00:44:28.480
to truck drivers to people
in and around cabinets

00:44:28.480 --> 00:44:29.920
and parliaments and kings.

00:44:29.920 --> 00:44:31.570
And we collect
that intelligence,

00:44:31.570 --> 00:44:33.500
put it into frameworks--

00:44:33.500 --> 00:44:35.320
this is a big
difference, frameworks--

00:44:35.320 --> 00:44:37.882
and then try to help our
clients see what's happening.

00:44:37.882 --> 00:44:39.340
GUY HORGAN: So in
a few interviews,

00:44:39.340 --> 00:44:42.740
I've heard you
described as a spy.

00:44:42.740 --> 00:44:44.305
RP EDDY: [LAUGHS] I'm not a spy.

00:44:44.305 --> 00:44:46.180
GUY HORGAN: Well, that's
what you always say.

00:44:46.180 --> 00:44:46.980
RP EDDY: Cut.

00:44:46.980 --> 00:44:51.356
GUY HORGAN: But I'm
curious, you can only

00:44:51.356 --> 00:44:53.230
speak in generalities,
I'm sure, but for some

00:44:53.230 --> 00:44:55.019
of the clients, who
are some clients,

00:44:55.019 --> 00:44:57.310
or what projects have you
done for clients that they're

00:44:57.310 --> 00:44:58.310
particularly happy with?

00:44:58.310 --> 00:45:00.950
What have you come and
discovered and shared?

00:45:00.950 --> 00:45:04.630
RP EDDY: So what's worth noting
is, what does the CIA actually

00:45:04.630 --> 00:45:05.777
do?

00:45:05.777 --> 00:45:08.110
Now, we believe it's-- well,
we saw the James Bond films

00:45:08.110 --> 00:45:09.310
and saw the Jason Bourne films.

00:45:09.310 --> 00:45:10.810
That must be something
like they do.

00:45:10.810 --> 00:45:12.330
That's not what they do.

00:45:12.330 --> 00:45:15.370
CIA, half the house is a
group of really, really

00:45:15.370 --> 00:45:17.607
smart analysts who
have, obviously,

00:45:17.607 --> 00:45:19.690
access to an extraordinary
amount of intelligence.

00:45:19.690 --> 00:45:22.330
They do analysis, and they try
to give warnings and insights

00:45:22.330 --> 00:45:23.844
to the executive branch.

00:45:23.844 --> 00:45:25.510
And then what's the
State Department do?

00:45:25.510 --> 00:45:27.176
Well, that's a little
better understood.

00:45:27.176 --> 00:45:29.950
The State Department is a series
of ambassadors and on down

00:45:29.950 --> 00:45:32.820
who represent the United
States to foreign governments.

00:45:32.820 --> 00:45:35.980
Ideally, Ergo has
aspects of both,

00:45:35.980 --> 00:45:38.230
where we help companies
and governments represent

00:45:38.230 --> 00:45:40.129
themselves and operate
in foreign areas

00:45:40.129 --> 00:45:42.420
and in the United States and
give them the intelligence

00:45:42.420 --> 00:45:43.200
to do so.

00:45:43.200 --> 00:45:44.040
Now, is that a spy?

00:45:44.040 --> 00:45:45.780
No, it's not.

00:45:45.780 --> 00:45:50.280
Examples that I'm proud of,
we have some great examples

00:45:50.280 --> 00:45:52.589
of helping the US
government defeat IEDs

00:45:52.589 --> 00:45:53.880
that were killing our soldiers.

00:45:56.329 --> 00:45:57.870
There was a great
organization called

00:45:57.870 --> 00:46:02.510
JIEDDO, the Joint IED
Defense Defeat Organization,

00:46:02.510 --> 00:46:03.262
out of the US DoD.

00:46:03.262 --> 00:46:05.220
It's a really cool example
of the US government

00:46:05.220 --> 00:46:07.477
getting its act together,
realizing there's a threat,

00:46:07.477 --> 00:46:09.060
and putting a huge
amount of resources

00:46:09.060 --> 00:46:12.030
at it very quickly and kind
of getting around bureaucracy.

00:46:12.030 --> 00:46:13.704
While working with
JIEDDO, we're very

00:46:13.704 --> 00:46:15.120
proud for some of
the work we were

00:46:15.120 --> 00:46:19.080
able to do to help stop some
of the most potent IEDs who

00:46:19.080 --> 00:46:22.500
were killing our soldiers in
Iraq as well as in Afghanistan.

00:46:22.500 --> 00:46:25.020
So that gives us huge pride.

00:46:25.020 --> 00:46:28.560
On a corporate side, we've had
a lot of work helping people not

00:46:28.560 --> 00:46:31.481
get involved with frauds.

00:46:31.481 --> 00:46:32.730
I'll give you a quick example.

00:46:32.730 --> 00:46:34.188
A very, very large
investment house

00:46:34.188 --> 00:46:38.490
wanted to start a whole new
fund in a non-American country,

00:46:38.490 --> 00:46:41.400
and they were going to build
it around a particular team

00:46:41.400 --> 00:46:43.050
and a team that had
an extraordinarily

00:46:43.050 --> 00:46:44.430
positive reputation.

00:46:44.430 --> 00:46:45.660
They hired us due diligence.

00:46:45.660 --> 00:46:48.540
It's a core aspect of our
business is diligence.

00:46:48.540 --> 00:46:53.190
And our diligence came back
and said, yes, by every report,

00:46:53.190 --> 00:46:55.317
these people are
extraordinary and influential.

00:46:55.317 --> 00:46:57.150
The problem is we've
discovered that they're

00:46:57.150 --> 00:46:59.310
under investigation
for corruption.

00:46:59.310 --> 00:47:00.060
They know it.

00:47:00.060 --> 00:47:01.080
They're lying to you.

00:47:01.080 --> 00:47:02.100
It's not public record.

00:47:02.100 --> 00:47:03.240
We were able to unearth it.

00:47:03.240 --> 00:47:05.490
So we saved that company,
by their estimates,

00:47:05.490 --> 00:47:08.170
a billion dollars of
embarrassment and cost

00:47:08.170 --> 00:47:09.420
by going into that enterprise.

00:47:09.420 --> 00:47:11.129
Because the allegations
of corruption

00:47:11.129 --> 00:47:12.420
would eventually have come out.

00:47:12.420 --> 00:47:14.860
And there's numerous
stories like that.

00:47:14.860 --> 00:47:20.200
But effectively
helping people create--

00:47:20.200 --> 00:47:22.620
in a world of opacity, we
try to create transparency.

00:47:22.620 --> 00:47:25.500
And it's no different than
what a Google search does,

00:47:25.500 --> 00:47:28.797
in many instances, but just
much bigger and more specific.

00:47:28.797 --> 00:47:30.630
GUY HORGAN: I was hoping
we could transition

00:47:30.630 --> 00:47:33.270
to start talking about a few
things that are going on today.

00:47:33.270 --> 00:47:34.860
You mentioned North
Korea, and it's something

00:47:34.860 --> 00:47:36.818
that I think everybody
here is concerned about.

00:47:36.818 --> 00:47:39.000
And I wonder if we're
almost past the point

00:47:39.000 --> 00:47:41.820
of needing a Cassandra
here, because it's

00:47:41.820 --> 00:47:42.840
a great fear by many.

00:47:42.840 --> 00:47:44.250
So I'll ask you that.

00:47:44.250 --> 00:47:49.160
And then number two, I'm
curious about the solution.

00:47:49.160 --> 00:47:51.430
So Cassandras have
alerted us to this.

00:47:51.430 --> 00:47:52.680
People are worried.

00:47:52.680 --> 00:47:54.239
What is there to be done?

00:47:54.239 --> 00:47:55.030
RP EDDY: All right.

00:47:55.030 --> 00:48:01.320
So first, Alan Robock who
is just-- the human race

00:48:01.320 --> 00:48:05.310
should be very thankful to
have Alan Robock amongst us.

00:48:05.310 --> 00:48:08.370
And his organization, as I said,
won a Nobel Prize last year,

00:48:08.370 --> 00:48:10.350
so he's not going unnoticed.

00:48:10.350 --> 00:48:13.494
But Alan's work on
global nuclear winter

00:48:13.494 --> 00:48:14.910
is a warning we
have to listen to.

00:48:14.910 --> 00:48:17.342
So that warning
hasn't been heard.

00:48:17.342 --> 00:48:19.800
We were talking earlier about
the amount of nuclear weapons

00:48:19.800 --> 00:48:22.474
that would likely be exchanged
if we had a nuclear war that.

00:48:22.474 --> 00:48:24.390
GUY HORGAN: You said 30
is the starting point.

00:48:24.390 --> 00:48:26.700
RP EDDY: I think 30's
your starting point.

00:48:26.700 --> 00:48:28.560
So if you think about
this series of targets

00:48:28.560 --> 00:48:31.020
that we would have
to hit in North Korea

00:48:31.020 --> 00:48:32.460
to have some degree
of confidence

00:48:32.460 --> 00:48:36.720
that Seoul isn't turned into
an inferno or Tokyo or Guam,

00:48:36.720 --> 00:48:38.976
or even California or even
DC, depending on where

00:48:38.976 --> 00:48:41.100
North Korea is in it's
nuclear weapons development,

00:48:41.100 --> 00:48:42.360
it's a large number of targets.

00:48:42.360 --> 00:48:44.130
GUY HORGAN: And you're saying
that those 30 strikes would

00:48:44.130 --> 00:48:45.030
need to happen quickly, then?

00:48:45.030 --> 00:48:45.320
So the artillery can't be--

00:48:45.320 --> 00:48:47.445
RP EDDY: It'd have to happen
almost simultaneously.

00:48:47.445 --> 00:48:49.560
It very much depends on
what your theory of war

00:48:49.560 --> 00:48:50.740
is in this instance.

00:48:50.740 --> 00:48:52.740
But the one that seems
to make most sense to me,

00:48:52.740 --> 00:48:55.073
and I think most sense to our
nuclear weapons planners--

00:48:55.073 --> 00:48:58.410
I can't say with huge
confidence-- is 30 at once.

00:48:58.410 --> 00:49:00.650
If we're going to do it,
we're going to do it.

00:49:00.650 --> 00:49:02.310
This isn't Hiroshima
or Nagasaki where

00:49:02.310 --> 00:49:05.020
we unveil the power of the sun--
have you ever seen it before,

00:49:05.020 --> 00:49:06.720
which is almost
a mystical thing.

00:49:06.720 --> 00:49:12.240
This is a tactical strike to
take out military capacities.

00:49:12.240 --> 00:49:14.460
So you're looking at
probably 30 minimum.

00:49:14.460 --> 00:49:16.594
Now, do we need a
warning about that?

00:49:16.594 --> 00:49:17.760
We're separating two things.

00:49:17.760 --> 00:49:19.968
Do we need a warning about
our risk with North Korea?

00:49:19.968 --> 00:49:20.550
Maybe not.

00:49:20.550 --> 00:49:21.730
I want to talk about it.

00:49:21.730 --> 00:49:23.700
Do we need a warning
about nuclear winter?

00:49:23.700 --> 00:49:24.577
Absolutely.

00:49:24.577 --> 00:49:26.160
All right, so we've
made that warning.

00:49:26.160 --> 00:49:29.130
Now, what's going
on with North Korea?

00:49:29.130 --> 00:49:32.390
As we sit here today, I think
we have a general sense of ease.

00:49:32.390 --> 00:49:33.450
Ah, we had the Olympics.

00:49:33.450 --> 00:49:35.130
It all went well.

00:49:35.130 --> 00:49:39.180
We're beginning to believe
that the North Koreans are just

00:49:39.180 --> 00:49:40.740
like we are.

00:49:40.740 --> 00:49:43.040
Don't the Russians love
their children too,

00:49:43.040 --> 00:49:46.257
as Sting and Police at one point
in the middle of the Cold War?

00:49:46.257 --> 00:49:47.340
And we said, yes, they do.

00:49:47.340 --> 00:49:48.923
And look, it all
worked out just fine.

00:49:48.923 --> 00:49:52.740
Well, the great gobbledygook
machine of Washington DC,

00:49:52.740 --> 00:49:56.060
which my view is actually
Colonel Mike Sheehan's view,

00:49:56.060 --> 00:49:58.590
Ambassador Mike Sheehan's view,
is sort of how policy really

00:49:58.590 --> 00:49:59.490
gets formed in DC.

00:49:59.490 --> 00:50:01.050
The State Department and
Brookings and Heritage

00:50:01.050 --> 00:50:02.490
and all these guys
kind of have a view,

00:50:02.490 --> 00:50:03.680
and they sort of say, ah.

00:50:03.680 --> 00:50:06.630
So the gobbledygook machine
view of North Korea for decades

00:50:06.630 --> 00:50:09.030
has been, they are rational.

00:50:09.030 --> 00:50:09.737
Don't worry.

00:50:09.737 --> 00:50:11.070
They don't want to nuke anybody.

00:50:11.070 --> 00:50:12.090
They don't want to get nuked.

00:50:12.090 --> 00:50:13.980
They know that they're
massively overpowered.

00:50:13.980 --> 00:50:15.530
We got this one.

00:50:15.530 --> 00:50:17.100
We will negotiate
our way out of it.

00:50:17.100 --> 00:50:19.730
That is the standard view.

00:50:19.730 --> 00:50:21.470
I hope it's right.

00:50:21.470 --> 00:50:23.430
I don't have much
evidence that it is.

00:50:23.430 --> 00:50:26.000
There is some recent
evidence, and only recent,

00:50:26.000 --> 00:50:29.180
by the third Kim that
they will be responsible

00:50:29.180 --> 00:50:32.090
nuclear weapons actors, because
they said they would be.

00:50:32.090 --> 00:50:35.780
If you look at the proliferation
of Israel, India, Pakistan,

00:50:35.780 --> 00:50:39.110
even South Africa, and Brazil,
when they are pursuing weapons

00:50:39.110 --> 00:50:42.290
programs, they all were very
clear to transmit to us,

00:50:42.290 --> 00:50:42.830
don't worry.

00:50:42.830 --> 00:50:45.030
We're not crazy.

00:50:45.030 --> 00:50:47.000
We will handle these
weapons responsibly.

00:50:47.000 --> 00:50:50.434
North Korea said the opposite
for three generations,

00:50:50.434 --> 00:50:52.350
three decades, however
you want to look at it.

00:50:52.350 --> 00:50:53.766
They've said, when
we get weapons,

00:50:53.766 --> 00:50:55.370
we're going to turn
Seoul into fire.

00:50:55.370 --> 00:50:57.050
We're going to unify the
peninsula under our rule.

00:50:57.050 --> 00:50:58.730
They've said very
aggressive things.

00:50:58.730 --> 00:51:03.590
Now, we want to
believe normalcy bias--

00:51:03.590 --> 00:51:05.360
confirmation bias
or normalcy bias.

00:51:05.360 --> 00:51:07.840
We want to believe that there
are going to be well-behaved.

00:51:07.840 --> 00:51:09.360
It just makes me feel good.

00:51:09.360 --> 00:51:10.610
I don't have the evidence yet.

00:51:10.610 --> 00:51:11.901
As I said, we've seen a little.

00:51:15.525 --> 00:51:17.650
The Trump Administration
is now grappling with this

00:51:17.650 --> 00:51:20.620
and trying to understand
the question themselves.

00:51:20.620 --> 00:51:23.132
North Korea has just offered
to have a negotiation with us.

00:51:23.132 --> 00:51:24.590
Everyone thinks
this is great news.

00:51:24.590 --> 00:51:25.892
It's not bad news.

00:51:25.892 --> 00:51:27.850
What North Korea is very
likely doing right now

00:51:27.850 --> 00:51:30.190
is trying to get the
technological advance

00:51:30.190 --> 00:51:33.190
to have the ICBM move
and deliver a payload.

00:51:33.190 --> 00:51:36.892
Right now, the ICBM moves
in the proper radius.

00:51:36.892 --> 00:51:39.100
But they have yet to prove
that they can successfully

00:51:39.100 --> 00:51:41.590
deliver a payload.

00:51:41.590 --> 00:51:44.819
When they prove that, which
is another technological feat,

00:51:44.819 --> 00:51:47.110
they will have the entire
set of cards in front of them

00:51:47.110 --> 00:51:49.782
that they need to negotiate,
if they want to negotiate.

00:51:49.782 --> 00:51:52.240
GUY HORGAN: So you're saying
you believe that it's possible

00:51:52.240 --> 00:51:55.150
that North Korea is delaying
such that they can miniaturize

00:51:55.150 --> 00:51:56.970
the payload so it
can be delivered,

00:51:56.970 --> 00:51:58.720
so that they're more
powerful negotiators?

00:51:58.720 --> 00:52:01.330
RP EDDY: I would bet
you dollars to donuts

00:52:01.330 --> 00:52:03.400
they are delaying as
long as they can to get

00:52:03.400 --> 00:52:06.940
that final re-entry proved.

00:52:06.940 --> 00:52:08.140
Why not?

00:52:08.140 --> 00:52:09.599
Now, there is good news.

00:52:09.599 --> 00:52:11.890
There are a series of things
inside the nuclear weapons

00:52:11.890 --> 00:52:14.980
complex of North Korea that may
have been built just to trade.

00:52:18.260 --> 00:52:18.910
Let's see.

00:52:18.910 --> 00:52:20.909
Now, there have been
countries that have turned.

00:52:20.909 --> 00:52:24.094
I mean, I mentioned South
Africa changed of goodwill.

00:52:24.094 --> 00:52:25.510
They were under
sanctions as well,

00:52:25.510 --> 00:52:27.310
but they got out of apartheid.

00:52:27.310 --> 00:52:30.930
Burma has had an extraordinary
change out of sanctions.

00:52:30.930 --> 00:52:33.850
They change to a
transparent country.

00:52:33.850 --> 00:52:35.820
Maybe North Korea will too.

00:52:35.820 --> 00:52:37.571
It has happened
before, and let's just

00:52:37.571 --> 00:52:39.070
hope it does in
this instance, or we

00:52:39.070 --> 00:52:41.140
are in for a very,
very difficult puzzle.

00:52:41.140 --> 00:52:42.600
North Korean
puzzle's a hard one.

00:52:42.600 --> 00:52:44.183
GUY HORGAN: So the
Cassandras that you

00:52:44.183 --> 00:52:46.740
listen to on this subject, what
do they say about the future?

00:52:46.740 --> 00:52:48.330
We agree it's a problem.

00:52:48.330 --> 00:52:50.710
We agree it's a
potential catastrophe.

00:52:50.710 --> 00:52:52.284
Is there a solution?

00:52:52.284 --> 00:52:53.950
RP EDDY: There is
absolutely a solution.

00:52:53.950 --> 00:52:56.230
If North Korea decides-- look,
we have something they want.

00:52:56.230 --> 00:52:57.396
They have something we want.

00:52:57.396 --> 00:52:59.560
There's a negotiation to be had.

00:52:59.560 --> 00:53:02.639
They want their children--
the leaders in North Korea,

00:53:02.639 --> 00:53:04.180
and there's probably
about 150 people

00:53:04.180 --> 00:53:06.910
who matter in that country right
now, as far as decision making.

00:53:06.910 --> 00:53:09.820
The leaders in North Korea,
like any good parent anywhere,

00:53:09.820 --> 00:53:12.040
probably wants their kids
to work at Google someday.

00:53:12.040 --> 00:53:14.706
They probably want their kids to
play in the Stanford basketball

00:53:14.706 --> 00:53:18.430
team or the University
of Illinois soccer team.

00:53:18.430 --> 00:53:20.710
Why not be part of this dream?

00:53:20.710 --> 00:53:23.650
And right now, of course, North
Korea can have none of that.

00:53:23.650 --> 00:53:25.090
They want to be
part of commerce.

00:53:25.090 --> 00:53:26.110
They want debt.

00:53:26.110 --> 00:53:28.840
They have massive oil reserves
offshore they want developed.

00:53:28.840 --> 00:53:30.700
They want to be wealthy.

00:53:30.700 --> 00:53:32.239
We can give that to them.

00:53:32.239 --> 00:53:33.780
But we're not going
give that to them

00:53:33.780 --> 00:53:34.860
till they give us
what we want, which

00:53:34.860 --> 00:53:36.240
is that they denuclearize.

00:53:36.240 --> 00:53:38.877
Now, there's a
number of outcomes.

00:53:38.877 --> 00:53:39.960
There's one I'm afraid of.

00:53:39.960 --> 00:53:42.030
One outcome I'm
not excited about

00:53:42.030 --> 00:53:44.490
would be if North Korea
and America strike

00:53:44.490 --> 00:53:47.460
a deal that says, we're
going to keep our nukes.

00:53:47.460 --> 00:53:49.470
We're going to keep our
short range missiles,

00:53:49.470 --> 00:53:51.210
but we'll give up the ICBMs.

00:53:51.210 --> 00:53:54.130
So you, America, can sleep
soundly in your beds,

00:53:54.130 --> 00:53:57.600
while Seoul and Tokyo
rip their hair out.

00:53:57.600 --> 00:54:00.060
That is one possible
negotiated outcome.

00:54:00.060 --> 00:54:03.720
If this administration, or any
administration negotiates that,

00:54:03.720 --> 00:54:06.360
it would be the absolute
end of Pax Americana,

00:54:06.360 --> 00:54:09.510
of the American promise to be a
global leader in good standing.

00:54:09.510 --> 00:54:12.780
It would be the end of that if
we left our allies high and dry

00:54:12.780 --> 00:54:13.320
like that.

00:54:13.320 --> 00:54:15.630
But it's going to be very
tempting, particularly

00:54:15.630 --> 00:54:18.600
to people who don't understand
the cost of destroying

00:54:18.600 --> 00:54:20.100
Pax Americana.

00:54:20.100 --> 00:54:23.370
Another outcome would be
total denuclearization.

00:54:23.370 --> 00:54:25.415
That would be a dream scenario.

00:54:25.415 --> 00:54:27.540
We would have to give them
a series of guarantees--

00:54:27.540 --> 00:54:29.550
not only let them back into
the world as I described.

00:54:29.550 --> 00:54:32.133
We'd have to probably guarantee
their security to some extent.

00:54:32.133 --> 00:54:34.594
We'd have to stop military
exercises, et cetera.

00:54:34.594 --> 00:54:36.260
Look, that would be
great for everybody.

00:54:36.260 --> 00:54:37.218
It'd be great for them.

00:54:37.218 --> 00:54:38.220
It'd be great for us.

00:54:38.220 --> 00:54:40.761
The only people who almost lose
a little bit in that scenario

00:54:40.761 --> 00:54:43.140
is China, because
they no longer have

00:54:43.140 --> 00:54:44.530
North Korea to keep us busy.

00:54:44.530 --> 00:54:46.530
And they've got, all of
a sudden, a country that

00:54:46.530 --> 00:54:48.870
could potentially be our
ally sitting on their border.

00:54:48.870 --> 00:54:50.578
They may not want
things to go that well.

00:54:52.890 --> 00:54:54.390
GUY HORGAN: Mr.
Bolton, John Bolton,

00:54:54.390 --> 00:54:56.700
has started in the White House.

00:54:56.700 --> 00:54:59.814
And of all the many
scary things that

00:54:59.814 --> 00:55:01.230
have happened in
the past year, it

00:55:01.230 --> 00:55:05.394
seems like the tenor of people
positing fears about him

00:55:05.394 --> 00:55:07.560
have been a little bit
different, that this is truly

00:55:07.560 --> 00:55:08.226
something scary.

00:55:08.226 --> 00:55:11.450
And it's almost like people--

00:55:11.450 --> 00:55:14.120
that his hawkish history
could be something different.

00:55:14.120 --> 00:55:16.620
Combining that with other people
leaving the White House who

00:55:16.620 --> 00:55:19.200
are generally supposed
to be moderating forces

00:55:19.200 --> 00:55:22.030
and the possibility of the
Mueller investigation coming

00:55:22.030 --> 00:55:25.680
to a head, and Trump now
truly needing a distraction,

00:55:25.680 --> 00:55:29.940
I'm wondering if you have any
fears about their deciding

00:55:29.940 --> 00:55:33.090
together with John Bolton
encouraging what he seems

00:55:33.090 --> 00:55:34.920
to have always
encouraged and Trump

00:55:34.920 --> 00:55:36.810
wanting to divert
attention from what

00:55:36.810 --> 00:55:38.580
might be coming down on him.

00:55:38.580 --> 00:55:41.310
Might that be a
combination of things

00:55:41.310 --> 00:55:43.260
that would be a perfect
storm for us to have

00:55:43.260 --> 00:55:45.510
a preemptive strike
and eliminate

00:55:45.510 --> 00:55:48.680
the possibility of even having
a negotiated disarmament?

00:55:48.680 --> 00:55:53.040
RP EDDY: So Guy, I wish I could
give you a lot of confidence

00:55:53.040 --> 00:55:54.910
that that's not
likely or possible.

00:55:54.910 --> 00:55:56.130
I just don't know.

00:55:56.130 --> 00:55:59.550
You know, it's a reasonable
Cassandra warning.

00:55:59.550 --> 00:56:02.520
But let me offer you a
slightly different view

00:56:02.520 --> 00:56:07.640
of the Bolton presence as our
national security advisor.

00:56:07.640 --> 00:56:09.560
First of all, we're all
very mimetic animals.

00:56:09.560 --> 00:56:14.030
So when the press shows
us a series of quotes

00:56:14.030 --> 00:56:16.610
from John Bolton about
destroying 10 floors of the UN,

00:56:16.610 --> 00:56:19.220
or how every other
nation is just

00:56:19.220 --> 00:56:22.610
a satellite that orbits
around our sun, et cetera,

00:56:22.610 --> 00:56:26.130
or how he's talked about a
preemptive strike on North

00:56:26.130 --> 00:56:28.650
Korea, et cetera, we could
walk out of the Iran deal,

00:56:28.650 --> 00:56:32.190
it's very easy to
get very concerned,

00:56:32.190 --> 00:56:34.710
particularly married with some
of the belligerent language

00:56:34.710 --> 00:56:37.680
we've seen from the president.

00:56:37.680 --> 00:56:38.850
I'm not sure that's wrong.

00:56:38.850 --> 00:56:40.530
But I have a slightly
different view.

00:56:40.530 --> 00:56:45.600
My view is where we were headed
before Bolton was scarier.

00:56:45.600 --> 00:56:47.520
So Rex Tillerson is gone.

00:56:47.520 --> 00:56:49.710
HR McMaster is gone.

00:56:49.710 --> 00:56:54.770
Madison, Kelly are still
around, but a huge number

00:56:54.770 --> 00:56:56.780
of people who were
given to Trump,

00:56:56.780 --> 00:56:59.780
foisted on Trump, selected
by Trump, have left.

00:56:59.780 --> 00:57:01.970
And what we're
beginning to see--

00:57:01.970 --> 00:57:05.510
and I think this was no surprise
to us four months ago when we

00:57:05.510 --> 00:57:08.010
began talking about this with
our clients, five months ago--

00:57:08.010 --> 00:57:11.000
we're seeing Trump begin
to get very comfortable

00:57:11.000 --> 00:57:13.520
in his presidency
and believe that he's

00:57:13.520 --> 00:57:15.780
able to make these
decisions on his own.

00:57:15.780 --> 00:57:20.570
So I call it TOHO,
T-O-H-O, Trump On His Own.

00:57:20.570 --> 00:57:23.240
And I think any
president on his own,

00:57:23.240 --> 00:57:25.490
any president making complex
decisions on his own,

00:57:25.490 --> 00:57:27.170
is bad news.

00:57:27.170 --> 00:57:30.830
I think a president who doesn't
have the depth of experience

00:57:30.830 --> 00:57:33.290
or lacks experience
as this president does

00:57:33.290 --> 00:57:34.770
is doubly bad news.

00:57:34.770 --> 00:57:37.070
So what I want to not
see more than anything

00:57:37.070 --> 00:57:38.940
is I don't want to
see Trump on his own.

00:57:38.940 --> 00:57:40.580
I don't want TOHO.

00:57:40.580 --> 00:57:43.790
I want smart, wise counsel
around every president,

00:57:43.790 --> 00:57:45.560
particularly this one.

00:57:45.560 --> 00:57:49.580
John Bolton and I have probably
wildly different opinions

00:57:49.580 --> 00:57:51.140
on how to exercise
American power,

00:57:51.140 --> 00:57:52.650
but we want the same thing.

00:57:52.650 --> 00:57:54.320
We believe in American
exceptionalism.

00:57:54.320 --> 00:57:58.520
We believe America has either
a right or an obligation,

00:57:58.520 --> 00:58:02.600
however you want to call
it, as the preeminent power.

00:58:02.600 --> 00:58:05.900
I tend to believe more that
Pax Americana, living up

00:58:05.900 --> 00:58:08.900
to the system of treaties we
wrote, being a positive ally,

00:58:08.900 --> 00:58:11.490
being there when people believe
we'll be there, even if it's

00:58:11.490 --> 00:58:14.660
a little late, is the way
America has power and benefits

00:58:14.660 --> 00:58:15.950
us around the world.

00:58:15.950 --> 00:58:18.200
I think his view is less
interested in alliances

00:58:18.200 --> 00:58:19.970
and more interested
in military force.

00:58:19.970 --> 00:58:21.970
That's bad, as far
as I'm concerned.

00:58:21.970 --> 00:58:25.520
What's good is that he is part
of the mainstream conversation.

00:58:25.520 --> 00:58:28.310
John Bolton is not Steve Bannon.

00:58:28.310 --> 00:58:29.690
I look at Steve
Bannon as the guy

00:58:29.690 --> 00:58:31.550
who wanted to tear
down the temple

00:58:31.550 --> 00:58:34.760
and had an extraordinary,
really outside the mainstream

00:58:34.760 --> 00:58:35.870
point of view of things.

00:58:35.870 --> 00:58:36.980
John Bolton is not there.

00:58:36.980 --> 00:58:40.460
He's way to the end, but
he's still in the mainstream.

00:58:40.460 --> 00:58:44.240
He's been an
undersecretary of defense.

00:58:44.240 --> 00:58:47.000
He's been a real member of the
foreign policy establishment

00:58:47.000 --> 00:58:47.910
for a long time.

00:58:47.910 --> 00:58:48.960
He knows how it works.

00:58:48.960 --> 00:58:50.420
He knows the value of
the civil servants.

00:58:50.420 --> 00:58:52.100
He knows the value
of the flag officers.

00:58:52.100 --> 00:58:53.600
He knows the value
of the diplomats.

00:58:53.600 --> 00:58:56.280
He knows how you can extract
value from alliances.

00:58:56.280 --> 00:58:58.520
So I'm hoping when he
sees a really crazy idea,

00:58:58.520 --> 00:58:59.130
he'll know it.

00:58:59.130 --> 00:59:00.831
The second thing
about John Bolton,

00:59:00.831 --> 00:59:03.080
he's got a really strong
personality and a really loud

00:59:03.080 --> 00:59:03.830
voice.

00:59:03.830 --> 00:59:08.360
So Trump on his own maybe will
get mitigated by John Bolton

00:59:08.360 --> 00:59:09.900
because he will be in the room.

00:59:09.900 --> 00:59:11.340
He won't be ignored.

00:59:11.340 --> 00:59:15.050
And Trump can't
toss him out like he

00:59:15.050 --> 00:59:16.460
tossed other people out.

00:59:16.460 --> 00:59:18.380
He can't toss him out
for being a globalist.

00:59:18.380 --> 00:59:19.260
He certainly isn't.

00:59:19.260 --> 00:59:21.510
He can't toss him out for
being more liberal than him.

00:59:21.510 --> 00:59:22.370
He certainly isn't.

00:59:22.370 --> 00:59:23.995
He can't toss him
out for being stupid.

00:59:23.995 --> 00:59:24.590
He isn't.

00:59:24.590 --> 00:59:28.700
So I don't think we're
going to see Trump ignoring

00:59:28.700 --> 00:59:30.414
Bolton for very long.

00:59:30.414 --> 00:59:31.580
We'll see how long it lasts.

00:59:31.580 --> 00:59:33.580
So what that means is
Trump won't be on his own.

00:59:33.580 --> 00:59:37.270
At least he'll have Bolton
joining Madison, Kelly,

00:59:37.270 --> 00:59:39.280
giving him what we hope
is wise counsel, which

00:59:39.280 --> 00:59:41.940
every president needs.

00:59:41.940 --> 00:59:44.100
GUY HORGAN: Final
question for you.

00:59:44.100 --> 00:59:45.934
This is not just a book,
but it's a movement

00:59:45.934 --> 00:59:47.016
that you're starting here.

00:59:47.016 --> 00:59:48.930
You have the awards
that you're giving out

00:59:48.930 --> 00:59:51.637
for Cassandras that you identify
as some of the most credible.

00:59:51.637 --> 00:59:53.970
But you have another one
called the White House National

00:59:53.970 --> 00:59:56.345
Warning Office that you and
Richard Clarke are proposing.

00:59:56.345 --> 00:59:58.844
So I was wondering if you could
talk a little bit about that

00:59:58.844 --> 01:00:00.704
and what your vision for it is.

01:00:00.704 --> 01:00:01.870
RP EDDY: Good question, Guy.

01:00:01.870 --> 01:00:03.280
Thanks for asking about that.

01:00:03.280 --> 01:00:07.890
So look, I mean, I truly believe
that Dick and I found something

01:00:07.890 --> 01:00:10.150
that previously existed,
was these Cassandras,

01:00:10.150 --> 01:00:11.983
there are people out
there who are giving us

01:00:11.983 --> 01:00:12.964
warnings of disasters.

01:00:12.964 --> 01:00:14.130
We know what they look like.

01:00:14.130 --> 01:00:16.380
We know how to separate the
Cassandra from the Chicken

01:00:16.380 --> 01:00:17.730
Little, and we need to do that.

01:00:17.730 --> 01:00:19.910
We have to institutionalize
this process.

01:00:19.910 --> 01:00:21.540
So the Cassandra
Award is one step.

01:00:21.540 --> 01:00:23.820
The other one is a
National Warning Office

01:00:23.820 --> 01:00:25.830
at the White House, inside
the Executive Office

01:00:25.830 --> 01:00:26.670
of the President.

01:00:26.670 --> 01:00:27.952
It needn't be a bureaucracy.

01:00:27.952 --> 01:00:29.910
I'm not talking about a
large number of people.

01:00:29.910 --> 01:00:32.201
I'm probably talking about
a half a dozen men and women

01:00:32.201 --> 01:00:35.070
who work within the EOP, so they
have an imprimatur of the White

01:00:35.070 --> 01:00:38.430
House, and now get to work
across the interagency,

01:00:38.430 --> 01:00:41.370
training people on Cassandra
theory and other theories,

01:00:41.370 --> 01:00:44.820
looking for warnings, and
trying to give voice to warnings

01:00:44.820 --> 01:00:47.260
that haven't been heard before.

01:00:47.260 --> 01:00:49.410
It would be an extraordinarily
wise thing to do.

01:00:49.410 --> 01:00:52.380
We no longer have the
National Intelligence Officer

01:00:52.380 --> 01:00:55.350
for Warning, the job
that Charlie Allen had

01:00:55.350 --> 01:00:57.780
where he foresaw Saddam's
invasion of Kuwait.

01:00:57.780 --> 01:00:59.130
That job's gone.

01:00:59.130 --> 01:01:00.760
We don't have that job anymore.

01:01:00.760 --> 01:01:03.810
We need an institution
inside government

01:01:03.810 --> 01:01:08.020
that's cross-cutting and is able
to see the forest for the trees

01:01:08.020 --> 01:01:10.200
and can find warnings
before others do.

01:01:10.200 --> 01:01:12.152
This organization could
create conferences,

01:01:12.152 --> 01:01:14.610
could create allies, could work
throughout the interagency,

01:01:14.610 --> 01:01:15.960
could task intelligence.

01:01:15.960 --> 01:01:18.360
It could take warnings,
put them through something

01:01:18.360 --> 01:01:21.360
like a Cassandra Coefficient
or other even better models--

01:01:21.360 --> 01:01:23.520
I don't care what it is,
no pride of authorship--

01:01:23.520 --> 01:01:27.000
and see if those warnings
deserve more attention or not.

01:01:27.000 --> 01:01:28.650
Why not build
something like this?

01:01:28.650 --> 01:01:35.845
Why not find a tool to
give voice to the warnings

01:01:35.845 --> 01:01:37.720
that we've been ignoring
time and time again?

01:01:37.720 --> 01:01:39.780
It would cost
effectively nothing,

01:01:39.780 --> 01:01:41.680
and the outcome could
be extraordinary.

01:01:41.680 --> 01:01:44.105
Think about the return I
mentioned on Fukushima.

01:01:44.105 --> 01:01:46.080
$50 million would have
saved $100 billion,

01:01:46.080 --> 01:01:48.600
$50 million, $100 billion--

01:01:48.600 --> 01:01:50.280
2,000 time return.

01:01:50.280 --> 01:01:52.760
A little bit of effort
to listen to the warnings

01:01:52.760 --> 01:01:54.960
could serve us dramatically.

01:01:54.960 --> 01:01:56.670
GUY HORGAN: I look
forward to it.

01:01:56.670 --> 01:01:57.350
RP EDDY: You can
be the head of it.

01:01:57.350 --> 01:01:58.516
GUY HORGAN: I appreciate it.

01:01:58.516 --> 01:01:59.990
I'll look forward to joining.

01:01:59.990 --> 01:02:02.275
"Warnings-- Finding Cassandras
to Stop Catastrophes."

01:02:02.275 --> 01:02:03.900
Thank you so much
for coming to Google.

01:02:03.900 --> 01:02:04.580
RP EDDY: Thanks very much, Guy.

01:02:04.580 --> 01:02:05.330
Great to be here.

01:02:05.330 --> 01:02:08.680
